{{Documentation subpage}}<!-- -------------------------------------------------------------- --NOTES -- -- NOTE A1: Unlike most Convert subtemplates, Convert/hand -- has 4 sections of special calculations to transform -- amounts in "hands.inches" notation, for x-to-hands, -- hands-to-x, range-to-hands, or hands-to-range of other -- units. -- -- NOTE D2: The logic changes any fractional hands into the -- decimals .1, .2 or .3 by checking parameter 2 to have "(" -- using {{padleft:|1|{{{2|(62)}}}&nbsp;}} and resets -- parameter 2, with the fraction multiplied by 100 & -- divided by 250, as one-tenth the multiple of 25. -- -- NOTE E3: For ranges, to extract prior conversion factor {b}, -- then {4} is decoded as having 3 values: (r)+(s)+{b}. -- The trick: b = ( {4}*2 - ( {4} ) ), where end-amount -- {b} doubles as b*2 in "(r)+(s)+ {b}*2" so subtracting -- {4} yields {b}*2-{b}, and hence {b} is extracted. -- -- NOTE R4: When hands are rounded, the markup checks if the -- result remainder +0.6 > 1 to add 1, rather than show -- x.35 rounded up to x.4, or rounded to the nearest whole -- hands as x.35 being x rather than x+1 as it should be. -- For single amounts, {3} contains the rounding level -- from "|0" while {4} contains the sigfig=n number. -- For ranges, {3} contains the second number of the range -- while {4} contains (r)+(s)+{b}, where r is round "|0" -- and (s) is from sigfig=n. The {b} is prior conversion -- factor from the input unit (such as cm with b=0.0254). -- -------------------------------------------------------------- --HISTORY: --07Sep2008 Created to convert hands as decimal amounts. --14Apr2011 Changed to convert as "hands.inches" notation. --14Apr2011 Added doc text to explain "hands.inches" +source. --15Apr2011 Added special calculations for range x-to-hands. --15Apr2011 Added special calculations for range hands-to-x. --15Apr2011 Put NOTES comments to explain template coding. --15Apr2011 Put HISTORY cmts to log major changes (not typos). --15Apr2011 Fixed range of hands to support wikilinked lk=on. --16Apr2011 Fixed ranges 72 options to wikilink by {d}=Dual/L*. --16Apr2011 Fixed round 0.3 as +1 hands not 0.4 (see NOTE R4). --16Apr2011 Fixed other-range {4}=( {4|..}*0 round 0} )+(0)+1. --01Jul2011 Set round to avoid nest of {precision} templates. --01Jul2011 Defaulted rounding to 2 if {1} has decimal > tenths. --01Jul2011 Set 1 amount in hands to round {4)=0 in output unit. -- --> The '''[[Template:Convert/hand]]''' converts [[w:Hand (unit)|hands]] of [[w:horse|horse]] height, such as with [[w:inch|inch]]es, [[w:metre|meters]] or cm. The conversion is 1 hand = 4 inches.<ref> "Horse Height Conversion", Onlineconversion.com, web: [http://www.onlineconversion.com/horse_height.htm OC-horse]. </ref> A fraction indicates inches, so "13.2" denotes 13 + 1/2 hands, rather than 2/10 or 1/5 hand. Examples: :*{&#123;convert|57|in|hand}} &rarr; {{convert|57|in|hand}} :*{&#123;convert|2|m|hand}} &rarr; {{convert|2|m|hand}} :*{&#123;convert|9.1|hand|in}} &nbsp; &nbsp; &rarr; {{convert|9.1|hand|in}} :*{&#123;convert|14.1|hand|in}} &nbsp; &nbsp; &rarr; {{convert|14.1|hand|in}} :*{&#123;convert|14.1|hand|cm}} &nbsp; &rarr; {{convert|14.1|hand|cm}} :*{&#123;convert|14.1|hand|in cm}} &rarr; {{convert|14.1|hand|in cm}} :*{&#123;convert|14.1|-|14.6|hand|cm}} &rarr; {{convert|14.1|-|14.6|hand|cm}} :*{&#123;convert|50|-|57|in|hand}} &rarr; {{convert|50|-|57|in|hand}} :*{&#123;convert|2|-|3|m|hand}} &rarr; {{convert|2|-|3|m|hand}} :*{&#123;convert|57|or|59|in|hand|abbr=on}} &rarr; {{convert|57|or|59|in|hand|abbr=on}} :*{&#123;convert|137|-|139|cm|hand|lk=on}} &rarr; {{convert|137|-|139|cm|hand|lk=on}} :*{&#123;convert|37|â€“|162|cm|hand|2|abbr=in|lk=out}} &rarr; {{convert|37|â€“|162|cm|hand|2|abbr=in|lk=out}}
Unlike most Convert subtemplates, Convert/hand has 4 sections of special calculations to transform amounts in "hands.inches" notation, for x-to-hands, hands-to-x, range-to-hands, or hands-to-range of other units. The logic changes any [[w:fraction|fraction]]al hands into decimals .1, .2 or .3 by checking parameter 2 to have "(" using {&#123;padleft:|1|{{{2|(62)}}}&nbsp;}} then resetting parameter 2, with the fraction multiplied by 100 & divided by 250, as one-tenth the multiple of 25. This is the first Convert subtemplate to calculate numbers which are not in decimal format (where ".1" is {{convert/numdisp|1/4}} not {{convert/numdisp|1/10}}), as would be a complex format also for [[w:hexadecimal|hexadecimal]] or binary numbers.
